		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						) Litera cuiusdam Pistoris Bononiensis ad Papam. Fideliter versa ex Jtalico
					</marginalia_text>
					<book title="Litera cujusdam pistoris Bononiensis ad papam"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Exemplari, impresso Florentia[e]. 
						Sic grauissima qua[e]q[ue] possu[n]t ad viuu[m] perstringi,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						) altè defixis aculeis
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						) faceti contemptus.
						Vnde prudentis est, Seipsu[m] armare efficaci arte;
						) aut seria facultate; aut =
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="270" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						aut aliquam cogenti vi, qua[e] à Seipsa dependeat, et omnes spernat mundi. 
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The letter of a certain Bolognese baker to the pope. Faithfully translated from an Italian copy, printed in Florence.
				Thus the weightiest matters can be seized to the quick, with barbs of witty contempt sunk deep.
				Whence the prudent to arm themselves with effective skill, 
				or, in some degree, with combined power, with which they depend on themselves, and spurn all things of the world.				
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
